  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a property that has been recently renovated is not straightforwardly simpler than selling one that has not been touched in twenty years. A fresh renovation removes some buyer objections, but it introduces others, and it creates disclosure obligations that sellers need to address carefully. Buyers who are experienced in Brisbane's inner east market are increasingly sophisticated about what they look for in renovated properties, and the way you document and present recent works can have a material effect on the sale price you achieve.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure obligations for recent works</h2>
      <p>Queensland's property disclosure framework requires sellers to disclose material facts about the property. Where renovations have been carried out, this includes whether relevant council approvals were obtained, whether the work was done by licensed tradespeople where that is required, and whether owner-builder warranty insurance applies.</p>

      <p>Any structural work, including extensions, new decks, garage conversions, and structural alterations to the existing building, requires a building approval from Brisbane City Council. Work done without approval is an undisclosed defect that can expose the seller to legal liability after settlement if the buyer discovers it. Before you list a renovated property, it is worth confirming with your conveyancer that all relevant approvals are on the public record. If they are not, obtaining retrospective approval or disclosing the absence of approval and adjusting your price expectations accordingly is the correct path. Attempting to conceal unapproved works is not.</p>

      <p>Owner-builder warranty insurance applies in Queensland when the owner has carried out, or arranged to carry out, residential building work valued at over $3,300 on a property they own. If you performed significant renovation work as an owner-builder and you are selling the property within 6 years and 3 months of the work being completed, you are required to provide the buyer with an owner-builder warranty insurance certificate under the Queensland Building and Construction Commission Act 1991. Your conveyancer will check whether this applies in your specific situation, but it is worth flagging early rather than discovering it days before settlement.</p>

      <p>For work carried out by licensed tradespeople, hold onto all invoices, contracts, and any compliance certificates (particularly for electrical, plumbing, and gas work). Buyers will ask for these during due diligence, and having them organised demonstrates that the work was done properly. Their absence raises questions you do not want asked during a negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers inspect differently in renovated homes</h2>
      <p>An experienced buyer purchasing a renovated home in Brisbane's inner east is not just looking at what the renovation looks like. They are looking at how well it was done and what might be underneath it. This is particularly true for older Queenslanders and post-war homes in suburbs like Morningside, Norman Park, Camp Hill, and Carina, where the original structure is typically timber and the risks associated with renovation quality are well understood by buyers who have been looking for a while.</p>

      <p>Building and pest inspectors engaged by buyers on recently renovated properties will look closely at areas where cosmetic work may have been done over existing problems: subfloor conditions, roof space, the junction between new and old materials, and any area where the original fabric of the building meets the renovation. A bathroom retile over an existing shower recess that was not properly waterproofed before tiling is a common problem that does not show up until the inspector's moisture meter finds it. Similarly, a kitchen renovation that involved partial replastering may conceal earlier moisture damage if the underlying cause was not addressed before the wall was finished.</p>

      <p>The way to address this is not to anticipate every possible finding but to be confident that the work was carried out to a standard that will withstand scrutiny. If you have concerns about specific areas, commissioning your own building and pest inspection before listing gives you the information you need to either address issues or disclose them accurately. A clean inspection report that you can offer to buyers proactively is a genuine marketing asset for a renovated property, because it removes a source of uncertainty and price conditioning during negotiations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to substantiate renovation quality in marketing</h2>
      <p>The claim "recently renovated" is so common in Brisbane property marketing that it has largely lost its meaning for buyers who have been searching for more than a few weeks. What it now signals, accurately or not, is that something has been done to the property that the seller wants you to notice. Whether buyers find that reassuring or cause for scrutiny depends entirely on what evidence is available to support the claim.</p>

      <p>The most effective way to market a quality renovation is to be specific and to provide documentation. Rather than "fully renovated kitchen," describe what was actually done: whether the cabinetry is custom or off-the-shelf, what appliances are included and their brands, whether the benchtop is stone or laminate, and whether any structural or plumbing changes were made. Buyers who care about kitchen quality will form an accurate view from that description. Buyers who do not care about kitchen quality are unaffected either way.</p>

      <p>If the renovation involved premium materials, include photographs that show the detail: the hardware, the joinery, the window reveals, the floor finish at the skirting junction. These are the things a buyer walking through will look at to assess whether a renovation was cheap or substantial, and showing them in marketing photography sets expectations accurately before the first inspection.</p>

      <p>Council approval documentation, trade invoices, and compliance certificates can be made available to buyers who request them during the due diligence period. Your agent should know these exist so they can reference them when buyers raise renovation quality as a point of negotiation or concern.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The impact of renovation scope on pricing expectations</h2>
      <p>Not all renovations add the same value, and buyers in Brisbane's inner east are reasonably good at calibrating this. A cosmetic renovation, meaning new paint, flooring, lighting, and kitchen and bathroom updates within the existing layout, adds meaningful value by removing the effort of those tasks from the buyer. A structural renovation that extended the living area, reconfigured the floor plan, or added a bedroom or bathroom adds a different kind of value and is typically reflected more significantly in comparable sales.</p>

      <p>Where sellers sometimes misjudge their pricing is in expecting buyers to pay for renovation cost rather than renovation value. The two are not the same. A $100,000 kitchen renovation in a suburb where kitchens of that quality are not common does not automatically add $100,000 to the price. What comparable sales show buyers will pay for is a more reliable guide than what the renovation cost. Your agent should be walking you through those comparables explicitly, not just validating your aspirations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains considerations for investment properties</h2>
      <p>For sellers disposing of an investment property that was renovated before sale, the capital gains tax (CGT) treatment of renovation costs is worth discussing with your accountant before you exchange contracts. As a general principle, capital improvements made to an investment property are added to the cost base of the asset for CGT purposes, which reduces the taxable gain on sale. This applies to genuine capital improvements, being work that adds to the value or extends the useful life of the property, as distinct from repairs and maintenance that simply restore the property to its original condition.</p>

      <p>The distinction between capital improvement and repair is not always obvious. Replacing a worn carpet with new carpet of equivalent quality is generally a repair. Replacing a worn carpet with polished timber floors is generally a capital improvement. Fixing a leaking roof is a repair. Adding insulation and a skylight while re-roofing is partly a capital improvement. Where renovation works span both categories, your accountant will need to apportion the costs appropriately. Organised trade invoices that describe the work in detail make this significantly easier than trying to reconstruct the breakdown from memory.</p>

      <p>If the property was your principal place of residence at any point during the ownership period, the CGT calculation is more complex and the relationship between the renovation timeline and the periods of PPOR occupancy is relevant. This is firmly in the territory of advice from a qualified accountant who knows your full financial circumstances, not a calculation you should attempt independently.</p>

